definition: To growl; to snarl.And wolves are gnarling who shall gnaw thee first. Shak.
An earnest; earnest money; money paid to bind a bargain.[Scot.] Arles penny, earnest money given to servants. Kersey.
A country seat; a country or suburban residence of somepretensions to elegance. Dryden. Cowper.
Having an air or manner characteristic of the stage;theatrical; artificial; as, a stagy tone or bearing; --chiefly useddepreciatively.
A short bar used by thieves to wrench doors open. [Written alsobettee.]The powerful betty, or the artful picklock. Arbuthnot.
Earlier form of Acknow. [Obs.] To be aknow, to acknowledge; toconfess. [Obs.]
An African genet (Genetta pardina). See Genet.
In an icy manner; coldly.Faultily faultless, icily regular, splendidly null, Dead perfection,no more. Tennyson.
The llama.
One who taws; a dresser of white leather.
The dried meat of the cocoanut, from which cocoanut oil isexpressed. [Written also cobra, copperah, coppra.]
A kind of whip for flogging criminals, formerly much used inRussia. The last is a tapering bundle of leather thongs twisted withwire and hardened, so that it mangles the flesh.
A porridge or gruel of maize meal and water, milk, or the like.[Sp. Amer.]
The blue titmouse. [Prov. Eng.]

An ethereal salt, or compound ether, consisting of an organicradical united with the residue of any oxygen acid, organic orinorganic; thus the natural fats are esters of glycerin and the fattyacids, oleic, etc.
Soiled; sullied; of a dark or dusky color; dark brown; dirty."Scraps of dingy paper." Macaulay.
An island in a river; an ait. [Obs.] "Osiers on their eights."Evelyn.

A name applied to various marine univalve shells; esp. to thoseof the genus Strombus, which are of large size. S. gigas is the largepink West Indian conch. The large king, queen, and cameo conchs areof the genus Cassis. See Cameo.
Made of jet, or like jet in color.The people . . . are of a jetty. Sir T. Browne.
Judea; also, a district inhabited by Jews; a Jews' quarter.Chaucer.Teaching throughout all Jewry. Luke xxiii. 5.
A kind of tape or braid. Shak.
of Mote. Chaucer.
To reck; to care. [Obs.] Shak.
A continuous noise or murmur.The chide of streams. Thomson.
To take to graze or pasture, at a certain sum; -- usedoriginally of the feeding of cattle in the king's forests, andcollecting the money for the same. Blackstone.
See Bort.
To make fast, as a rope, by taking several turns with it rounda pin, cleat, or kevel. Totten.
A larva.
Shape; build; form of structure; as, the built of a ship.[Obs.] Dryden.
A bitter purgative principle in aloes.
To care for medicinally or surgically; to manage in the use ofremedies or appliances; as, to treat a disease, a wound, or apatient.

The tincture red, indicated in seals and engraved figures ofescutcheons by parallel vertical lines. Hence, used poetically for ared color or that which is red.His sev'n-fold targe a field of gules did stain In which two swordshe bore; his word, "Divide and reign." P. Fletcher.Follow thy drum; With man's blood paint the ground; gules, gules.Shak.Let's march to rest and set in gules, like suns. Beau. & Fl.
See Yeasty. Shak.
To cast out; to evict; to dispossess; as, to eject tenants froman estate.

One of the forms which a verb takes by inflection or by addingauxiliary words, so as to indicate the time of the action or eventsignified; the modification which verbs undergo for the indication oftime.
To brood; to incubate. [Obs.][Tortoises] covey a whole year before they hatch. Holland.
A noisy quarrel; loud, angry contention; a wrangle; a tumult;as, a drunken brawl.His sports were hindered by the brawls. Shak.
A small-sized, well-proportioned, Spanish horse; a jennet.Shak.
A series of beds of clay and marl in the South of England,between the upper and lower greensand of the Cretaceous period.
A kind of military cap or headress.
2d per. sing. of Shall.
Consisting of, or covered with, tar; like tar.
The substances which inclose the ore on every side.

Sheet; surface; all that portion of a surface that iscontinuous in such a way that it is possible to pass from any onepoint of the portion to any other point of the portion withoutleaving the surface. Thus, some hyperboloids have one nappe, and somehave two.
Hateful; detestable. [Obs.]

A plant having twigs suitable for making brooms to sweep withwhen bound together; esp., the Cytisus scoparius of Western Europe,which is a low shrub with long, straight, green, angular branches,mintue leaves, and large yellow flowers.No gypsy cowered o'er fires of furze and broom. Wordsworth.

The crested screamer of Brazil (Palamedea, or Chauna,chavaria), so called in imitation of its notes; -- called alsochauna, and faithful kamichi. It is often domesticated and is usefulin guarding other poultry. See Kamichi.
Like ale; as, an alish taste.
A water course. [Prov. Eng.]
, old imp. of Drive. [Obs.]
The stage in a theater; as, to go upon the boards, to enterupon the theatrical profession.
Any substance having a peculiar glassy appearance, and aconchoidal fracture, and usually produced by fusion.
The upper horizontal part of a step, on which the foot isplaced.
A sty on the eye. See Styan.
Titanic.The Titan physical difficulties of his enterprise. I. Taylor.
See 2d Loch.
A dowse. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
A giant. [Obs.] Beau & Fl.
Arched; as, archy brows.
Having (such) a tone; -- chiefly used in composition; as, high-toned; sweet-toned. Toned paper, paper having a slight tint, indistinction from paper which is quite white.
A cone of paper which is placed in a vessel of lard or otherfat, and used as a taper. [Prov. Eng.]
A comedian. [Obs.] Steele.
of Mete, to dream. Chaucer.
Potential energy; negative value of the force function.

Belonging to,or concerning, a focus; as, a focal point. Focaldistance, or length,of a lens or mirror (Opt.), the distance of thefocus from the surface of the lens or mirror, or more exactly, in thecase of a lens, from its optical center. --Focal distance of atelescope, the distance of the image of an object from the objectglass.
See Groan. [Obs.]
Of the nature of agate, or containing agate.
A plant of the genus Geum, esp. Geum urbanum, or herb bennet.
To rule; to govern. [Obs.] "To regle their lives." Fuller.

To cease to sleep; to come out of a state of natural sleep;and, figuratively, out of a state resembling sleep, as inaction ordeath.The national spirit again awoke. Freeman.Awake to righteousness, and sin not. 1 Cor. xv. 34.
A paddock, or toad. Padow pipe. (Bot.) See Paddock pipe, underPaddock.

A white to gray volcanic tufa, formed of decomposed trachyticcinders; -- sometimes used as a cement. Hence, a coarse sort ofplaster or mortar, durable in water, and used to line cisterns andother reservoirs of water. [Formerly written also tarras, tarrace,terras.]
Sap green. [China]
imp. & p. p. of Slink.
An icicle. [Prov. Eng.]
One of the terminal divisions of a limb appendage; a finger ortoe.The ruminants have the "cloven foot," i. e., two hoofed digits oneach foot. Owen.
Peace; security; agreement. [Obs.] Gower.
A trial impression, as from type, taken for correction orexamination; -- called also proof sheet.
One who topes, or drinks frequently or to excess; a drunkard; asot.
A crossbow. See Prod, 3.
To persist in staying or visiting.I've charged thee not to haunt about my doors. Shak.
Bulged; bulging; bending, or tending to bend, outward.[Colloq.]
To chirp, as a young bird.
A sedgelike plant (Cyperus esculentus) producing edible tubers,native about the Mediterranean, now cultivated in many regions; theearth almond.
An annoyer. [Obs.] Tusser.
An old English game; -- called also lawn billiards.
One who believes in the existence of a God, but denies revealedreligion; a freethinker.
An island. See Eyot.
imp. of Swell.
A sterile transformed stamen.
Third. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A small variety of the Lima bean (Phaseolus lunatus).
See Lamella.

A kind of millet, cultivated throughout Asia, and introducedinto the south of Europe; a variety of Sorghum vulgare; -- calledalso Indian millet, and Guinea corn. [Written also dhoorra, dhurra,doura, etc.]

Pertaining to, derived from, or contained in, oil; as, oleicacid, an acid of the acrylic acid series found combined with glycerylin the form of olein in certain animal and vegetable fats and oils,such as sperm oil, olive oil, etc. At low temperatures the acid iscrystalline, but melts to an oily liquid above 14
One of the segments of the abdomen or post-abdomen ofarthropods.
One who loses by sloth or neglect; a worthless person; a lorel.[Archaic] Spenser.One sad losel soils a name for aye. Byron.
A premium given for a loan, or for a charter or other privilegegranted to a company; as the bank paid a bonus for its charter.Bouvier.
of Lose. Chaucer.
To make a bride of. [Obs.]
Hence. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A dove. [Obs.] Chaucer.

To lay within; hence, to insert, as pieces of pearl, iviry,choice woods, or the like, in a groundwork of some other material; toform an ornamental surface; to diversify or adorn with insertions.Look,how the floor of heaven Is thick inlaid with patines of brightgold. Shak.But these things are . . . borrowed by the monks to inlay theirstory. Milton.
To poke; to thrust. [Obs.] Holland.
See Twill.
Increasing strength, or the tone of the animal system;obviating the effects of debility, and restoring heatly functions.Tononic spasm. (Med.) See the Note under Spasm.
See Gypsum. [Obs.] Pococke.

A picture cut in wood or metal, or made by impression; a cut; aplate. [Obs.]At Venice they put out very curious stamps of the several edificeswhich are most famous for their beauty and magnificence. Addison.
The letter h or H.
A vat or tub in which the mash is made; a mash tub. Ure.

To make unsuitable or incompetent; to deprive of the strength,skill, or proper qualities for anything; to disable; to incapacitate;to disqualify; as, sickness unfits a man for labor; sin unfits us forthe society of holy beings.
A tablet; a register; hence, a list or scheme inscribed on atablet. [R.] Sir T. Browne.
A lot consisting of sixty pieces; -- a term applied in someBaltic ports to loose goods.
Passing opportunities seized; snatches.It has been writ by catches with many intervals. Locke.

A severe paroxysmal pain in the abdomen, due to spasm,obstruction, or distention of some one of the hollow viscera. Hepaticcolic, the severe pain produced by the passage of a gallstone fromthe liver or gall bladder through the bile duct.-- Intestinal colic, or Ordinary colic, pain due to distention ofthe intestines by gas.-- Lead colic, Painter's colic, a violent form of intestinal colic,associated with obstinate constipation, produced by chronic leadpoisoning.-- Renal colic, the severe pain produced by the passage of acalculus from the kidney through the ureter.-- Wind colic. See Intestinal colic, above.
An old measure of length in France, containing six French feet,or about 6.3946 French feet.
A hinge. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The twelfth part of a troy pound.
To sink or lay, as in a bed; to deposit in a partly inclosingmass, as of clay or mortar; to cover, as with earth, sand, etc.
Queer, and fitted to provoke laughter; ludicrous from oddity;amusing and strange.
A sudden thrust or pass, as with a sword.

To cry down; to censure as faulty, mean, or worthless; toclamor against; to blame clamorously; to discredit; to disparage.For small errors they whole plays decry. Dryden.Measures which are extolled by one half of the kingdom are naturallydecried by the other. Addison.
Bohea tea, an inferior kind of black tea. See under Tea.

Pertaining to, or obtained from, apples; as, malic acid. Malicacid, a hydroxy acid obtained as a substance which is sirupy orcrystallized with difficulty, and has a strong but pleasant sourtaste. It occurs in many fruits, as in green apples, currants, etc.It is levorotatory or dextrorotatory according to the temperature andconcentration. An artificial variety is a derivative of succinicacid, but has no action on polarized light, and thus malic acid is aremarkable case of physical isomerism.
Denoting pound weight for one thousand; -- used in combination,with respect to nails; as, tenpenny nails, nails of which onethousand weight ten pounds.
A tun. [Obs.] Chaucer.

A figure in which a word is separated or repeated by way ofemphasis, so as not only to signify the individual thing denoted byit, but also its peculiar attribute or quality; as, "His wife's awife indeed." Bailey.
A rapid in some rivers; as, the Sault Ste. Marie. [U.S.]Bartlett.
Merrily; showily. See gaily.
A magistrate; one of a body of five magistrates chosen by thepeople of ancient Sparta. They exercised control even over the king.
The first stomach of ruminants; the paunch; the fardingbag. SeeIllust. below.
Pleasant; jocose. [R.]The joyous and lepid consul. Sydney Smith.
Negligence or fault, as distinguishable from dolus (deceit,fraud), which implies intent, culpa being imputable to defect ofintellect, dolus to defect of heart. Wharton.
Foolishly; fondly. [Obs.] Spenser.
A proportional part or share; the share or proportion assignedto each in a division. "Quota of troops and money." Motley.
The worn side of the bank of a river. See 4th Fret, n., 4.
The Muse who presided over lyric and amatory poetry.

To bring one's self; to make headway; to veer; as, to fetchabout; to fetch to windward. Totten. To fetch away (Naut.), to breakloose; to roll slide to leeward.-- To fetch and carry, to serve obsequiously, like a trainedspaniel.
A nest: a repository for the eggs of birds, insects, etc.; abreeding place; esp., the place or substance where parasites or thegerms of a disease effect lodgment or are developed.

Of or pertaining to the Saxons, their country, or theirlanguage.(b) Anglo-Saxon.(c) Of or pertaining to Saxony or its inhabitants. Saxon blue(Dyeing), a deep blue liquid used in dyeing, and obtained bydissolving indigo in concentrated sulphuric acid. Brande & C.-- Saxon green (Dyeing), a green color produced by dyeing withyellow upon a ground of Saxon blue.
Of or pertaining to sheep; consisting of sheep.
A funeral song; an elegy.
To go, or move (in a certain manner); -- usually with out, off,along, etc. [Colloq.]  E. N. Wescott.
A running knot, or loop, which binds the closer the more it isdrawn.
The course or way which is traveled or passed, or is to bepassed; a passing; a course; a road or path; a march.Wide through the furzy field their route they take. Gay.
Profitable; useful. [Obs.]
A few silk threads or horsehairs, or a strip of linen or thelike, introduced beneath the skin by a knife or needle, so as to forman issue; also, the issue so formed.
A game at dice, properly called novem quinque (L., nine five),the two principal throws being nine and five. [Obs.] Shak.
Flax. See Linen. [Obs.]

See Draw, v. t. & i. Drawn butter, butter melter and preparedto be used as a sort of gravy.-- Drawn fowl, an eviscerated fowl.-- Drawn game or battle, one in which neither party wins; oneequally contested.-- Drawn fox, one driven from cover. Shak.-- Drawn work, ornamental work made by drawing out threads from finecloth, and uniting the cross threads, to form a pattern.
A provider; a purveyor; a caterer. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The offspring of animals, either a single animal or offspringcollectively.[The egg] bursting with kindly rupture, forth disclosed Their callowyoung. Milton.With young, with child; pregnant.
See Sloakan.
Flimsy; vague; deceptive. [Obs.] Ascham.
See Fit a song. [Archaic]
Same as Tabor.  Nahum ii. 7.
To strike together so as to produce a ringing metallic sound.The fierce Caretes . . . clanged their sounding arms. Prior.
See Ochery.
A light, loose dress or robe. [Also written camus.] [Obs.]All in a camis light of purple silk. Spenser.
The jaws, or the fleshy parts about them. See Chap. "Open yourchaps again." Shak.
To melt. [Obs.] Mortimer.
To trust. [Obs.] Chaucer.
The Baltic or variable cod (Gadus callarias), by some believedto be the young of the common codfish.
A forked tool used by clothiers in dressing cloth.
a flat heap of moist, crushed silver ore, prepared for thepatio process.
To squint; to stare. [Obs.]
A small New Zealand owl (Sceloglaux albifacies). It has shortwings and long legs, and lives chiefly on the ground.
The Turkish language of the Yakuts, a Mongolian people ofnortheastern Siberia, which is lingua franca over much of easternSiberia.
One of a race of a brown or copper complexion in the MalayPeninsula and the western islands of the Indian Archipelago.

Of or pertaining to slime; resembling slime; of the nature ofslime; viscous; glutinous; also, covered or daubed with slime;yielding, or abounding in, slime.Slimy things did crawl with legs Upon the slimy sea. Coleridge.
Opened; in blossom or having blossomed, as a flower. Shak.
The slope or angle to which the cutting edge of a tool, as aplane, is ground. Grier.
See Eloign.

Any one of a large group of bright-colored clamatorial birdsbelonging to Pitta, and allied genera of the family Pittidæ. Most ofthe species are varied with three or more colors, such as blue,green, crimson, yellow, purple, and black. They are called alsoground thrushes, and Old World ant thrushes; but they are not relatedto the true thrushes.
To make the noise, or utter the call, of a brooding hen. Ray.
A palace; a seraglio; also, in the East, a place for theaccommodation of travelers; a caravansary, or rest house.
Frothy matter raised on liquids by boiling, effervescence, oragitation; froth; foam; scum.Materials dark and crude, Of spiritous and fiery spume. Milton.
A small wheel formerly fixed to the pan of firelocks fordischarging them. Crabb.
A wood. See Hurst.
Good of its kind; -- variously used as implying substantial,real, fixed, sure, etc., and specif., of buildings, made of brick andmortar. [India]
A long garment, descending to the ankles, worn by Roman women.The stola was not allowed to be worn by courtesans, or by women whohad been divorced from their husbands. Fairholt.
Malignity. [P.] Burton.
To anoint. [Obs.] Sir T. North.
To remove the turns of (a rope or cable) from the bits; as, tounbit a cable. Totten.
The chaffinch.
A striving; an effort; a conatus.A nisus or energizing towards a presented object. Hickok.

To put off; to postpone to a future time; to delay theexecution of; to delay; to withhold.Defer the spoil of the city until night. Shak.God . . . will not long defer To vindicate the glory of his name.Milton.
Cloth or flax dipped in warm water or medicaments and appliedto a hurt or sore.
The edges or lower borders of the roof of a building, whichoverhang the walls, and cast off the water that falls on the roof.
A suffix or terminal formative, much used in anatomical terms,and signifying skin, integument, covering; as, blastoderm, ectoderm,etc.

Bad, evil, or pernicious, in the highest degree, whether in aphysical or moral sense. See Worse. "Heard so oft in worst extremes."Milton.I have a wife, the worst that may be. Chaucer.If thou hadst not been born the worst of men, Thou hadst been a knaveand flatterer. Shak.
An East Indian Weight of 11/3 pounds.
To supply with money. [Obs.]

A gentlewoman; -- an appellation or courteous form of addressgiven to a lady, especially an elderly or a married lady; -- muchused in the address, at the beginning of a letter, to a woman. Thecorresponding word in addressing a man is Sir.
Of or pertaining to ancient Scandinavia, or to the languagespoken by its inhabitants.
Same as Oillet.
The title of the native sovereigns of Hyderabad, in India,since 1719.
Compar. of Low, a.
An East Indian insectivorous mammal (Gymnura Rafflesii),somewhat like a rat in appearance, but allied to the hedgehog.

The organ formed by the combination or union into one body ofstem and leaf, and often bearing the fructification; as, the frond ofa fern or of a lichen or seaweed; also, the peculiar leaf of a palmtree.
See Lack. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A circular frame on which cadgers carry hawks for sale.
A suffix meaning a ruler, as in monarch (a sole ruler).
The suslik.
A whorl. See Whorl.
The European green woodpecker; -- also called ecall, eaquall,yaffle. [Prov. Eng.]

A vessel having one mast and fore-and-aft rig, consisting of aboom-and-gaff mainsail, jibs, staysail, and gaff topsail. The typicalsloop has a fixed bowsprit, topmast, and standing rigging, whilethose of a cutter are capable of being readily shifted. The sloopusually carries a centerboard, and depends for stability upon breadthof beam rather than depth of keel. The two types have rapidlyapproximated since 1880. One radical distinction is that a slop maycarry a centerboard. See Cutter, and Illustration in Appendix. Sloopof war, formerly, a vessel of war rigged either as a ship, brig, orschooner, and mounting from ten to thirty-two guns; now, any warvessel larger than a gunboat, and carrying guns on one deck only.
A gem of an azure color. [Obs.]
A gambling game in vogue in the eighteenth century. Thackeray.
To manage a canoe, or voyage in a canoe.
To hide; to skulk. [Scot.]He at length escaped them by derning himself in a foxearth. H.Miller.
A sunken channel or groove, usually vertical. See Triglyph.
The chigoe.
In an apt or suitable manner; fitly; properly; pertinently;appropriately; readily.

A wind instrument of music; a trumpet, or sound of a trumpet; -- used chiefly in Scripture and poetry.We shall all be changed, in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, atthe last trump. 1 Cor. xv. 51, 52.The wakeful trump of doom. Milton.
By day, or every day; in the daytime. [Obs.] Fielding.
Silver, pounded into ingots of the shape of a shoe, and used ascurrency. The most common weight is about one pound troy. [China]McElrath.
Of or pertaining to a duke.His ducal cap was to be exchanged for a kingly crown. Motley.
One who places things in a pile.
imp. of Glide. Chaucer.
See Dun crow, under Dun, a.
A strap of leather; especially, one used for fasteninganything.And nails for loosened spears, and thongs for shields, provide.Dryden.Thong seal (Zoöl.), the bearded seal. See the Note under Seal.
Stucco. [Obs.]
See Calk.

The national god of the Philistines, represented with the faceand hands and upper part of a man, and the tail of a fish. W. Smith.This day a solemn feast the people hold To Dagon, their sea idol.Milton.They brought it into the house of Dagon. 1 Sam. v. 2.
A genus of small insectivores including the common Europeanmole.
A kind of helmet worn in the 14th, 15th, and 16th centuries.
To pour, or take, or let go, out of a bag or bags.
In the Orkney and Shetland Islands, beef and mutton hung anddried, but not salted. [Scot.] [Written also vivda.] Jamieson.
Thick; crowded; compact; dense. [Obs.]This spiss and . . . copious, yet concise, treatise. Brerewood.
imp. of Swear.
The black currant; also, the wild plum. [Prov. Eng.]
To feel or express undue care and anxiety; to manifestdisquietude or pain; to be fretful; to chafe; as, the child worries;the horse worries.
A pack sack to be swung on either side of a packsaddle.[Western U. S.]
To disturb. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To adorn in a showy manner; to dress or equip ostentatiously; -- often followed by up; as, to prank up the body. See Prink.In sumptuous tire she joyed herself to prank. Spenser.
The back.
A melted mass of turpentine, tallow, etc., with which themasts, sides, and bottom of a ship are smeared for lubrication. Ham.Nav. Encyc.
A small mortar on a gun carriage, in use before the howitzer.
To unbend. [R.] Fuller.
See Inure.
See Pattee.
The tapir.
A genus of trees, some species of which produce edible fruit;the mulberry. See Mulberry.

Designating, or pertaining to, an important linguistic stock ofNorth American Indians of the southwestern United States andnorthwestern Mexico, nearly all agriculturists and adept potters andbasket makers. Their usual dwelling is the brush wikiup, and in theirnative state they wear little clothing. The Yuma, Maricopa, Mohave,Walapi, and Yavapai are among the chief tribes, all of fine physique.
A kind of silk lace or light netting, used for veils, etc.
p. p. of Shear.
A species of wild goose (Branta bernicla) -- called also brentand brand goose. The name is also applied to other related species.
Bright; luminous; clear; unclouded.Like distant thunder on a shiny day. Dryden.

The young or embryo of an animal in the womb, or in the egg;often restricted to the later stages in the development of viviparousand oviparous animals, embryo being applied to the earlier stages.[Written also foetus.]
A pool; a plash. [Obs.] Spenser.
A piece of metal prepared to be made into something by afurther operation, as a coin, screw, nuts.
A live or glowing coal; a glede. [Archaic] Chaucer. Longfellow.

Any definite quantity, or aggregate of quantities or magnitudestaken as one, or for which 1 is made to stand in calculation; thus,in a table of natural sines, the radius of the circle is regarded asunity.
In a bad manner; poorly; not well; unskillfully; imperfectly;unfortunately; grievously; so as to cause harm; disagreeably;seriously.
An assembly; hence, the place of assembly, especially themarket place, in an ancient Greek city.
A prefix signifying half.
Active; brisk; nimble; quick; sharp. [Archaic or Prov. Eng. &Scot.]That horny-handed, snell, peremptory little man. Dr. J. Brown.
To give birth; to produce young.This queen Genissa childing died. Warner.It chanced within two days they childed both. Latimer.

In a lower, subject, or subordinate condition; in subjection; -- used chiefly in a few idiomatic phrases; as, to bring under, toreduce to subjection; to subdue; to keep under, to keep insubjection; to control; to go under, to be unsuccessful; to fail.I keep under my body, and bring it into subjection. 1 Cor. ix. 27.The minstrel fell, but the foeman's chain Could not bring his proudsoul under. Moore.
A combining form denoting a discourse, treatise, doctrine,theory, science; as, theology, geology, biology, mineralogy.
To see; to look; to mind. [Obs.] Wyclif.
A king and lawgiver of Crete, fabled to be the son of Jupiterand Europa. After death he was made a judge in the Lower Regions.
A corruption of pair royal. See under Pair, n.
Narrow. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To stop; to cease. [Archaic]They can not stint till no thing be left. Chaucer.And stint thou too, I pray thee. Shak.The damsel stinted in her song. Sir W. Scott.
To summon. [Obs.] Chaucer.

To move or turn round rapidly; to whirl round; to move and turnrapidly with the fingers.See ruddy maids, Some taught with dexterous hand to twirl the wheel.Dodsley.No more beneath soft eve's consenting star Fandango twirls his jocundcastanet. Byron.
Eatable; fruitful. [R.] Chapman.
To disarm. Sir T. Browne.
Poisonous; malignant; malicious. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A soft twilled silk fabric much used for women's dresses; --called also surah silk.
See Pavan.
One who hides or conceals.
The shoulder. [Obs.] Spenser.
Consisting or partaking of marl; resembling marl; aboundingwith marl.
To cover or decorate with slender pieces of wood, metal, ivory,etc.; to inlay. [Obs.] Spenser.
To set sail. [Obs.] Acts xiii. 13.
Musty; moldy; slimy; mucous.-- Mu"cid*ness, n.
To slip on the whelps or the barrel of a capstan or windlass; -- said of a cable or hawser.
A thin, flying cloud; a rack.
A case in which certain goods, as tea, opium, etc., aretransported; hence, the quantity which such a case contains.
To bar in; to secure. [Obs.]To imbar their crooked titles. Shak.
See 2d Settee.

One of the twelve portions into which the year is divided; thetwelfth part of a year, corresponding nearly to the length of asynodic revolution of the moon, -- whence the name. In popular use, aperiod of four weeks is often called a month.
To shell. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.]
Alluvial matter on the surface of land, not of recent origin.R. Jameson.
A bay window. See Bay window.The beams that thro' the oriel shine Make prisms in every carvenglass. Tennyson.
Affected by the tide; having a tide. "The tided Thames." Bp.Hall.
An end; conclusion. It is often placed at the end of a book.
A person appointed according to law to try challenges ofjurors; a trior. Burrill.
That part of a pilaster which is between the base and thecapital, corresponding to the shaft of a column.
A grove. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Having a pattern or colors which resemble a Scotch plaid;checkered or marked with bars or stripes at right angles to oneanother; as, plaid muslin.
To black or foul with soot. [R.]Sootied with noisome smoke. Chapman.
A tap or stamp of the foot as a warning of intent to attack; --called also attack.
See Ovine.
Pertaining to, or like, algæ.
of Leave. Chaucer.
A hart or stag three years old. [Written also spaid, spayade.]
A white, waxy substance, forming the essential part ofspermaceti.
A group of mammals which formerly included the Carnivora,Insectivora, Marsupialia, and lemurs, but is now often restricted tothe Carnivora.
To place in huts; to live in huts; as, to hut troops in winterquarters.The troops hutted among the heights of Morristown. W. Irving.
Sarsaparilla. [Written also sarza.]
A native prince or king; also, a landholder or person ofimportance in the agricultural districts. [India]

Originally, a covered porch with seats, at a house door; theDutch stoep as introduced by the Dutch into New York. Afterward, anout-of-door flight of stairs of from seven to fourteen steps, withplatform and parapets, leading to an entrance door some distanceabove the street; the French perron. Hence, any porch, platform,entrance stairway, or small veranda, at a house door. [U. S.]
A disease in the feet of cattle; laminitis. Crabb.
To yaup.
Same as Pixy.
A knife or short dagger, esp. that in use among the Highlandersof Scotland. [Variously spelt.] "His skean, or pistol." Spenser.
Belonging to, or resembling, a bat. "Batty wings." Shak.
Originally, a laborer on canals for internal navigation; hence,a laborer on other public works, as in building railroads,embankments, etc. [Eng.]
Furnished with keys; as, a keyed instrument; also, set to akey, as a tune. Keyed bugle. See Kent bugle.
Pertaining to a house. Addison.
An arched structure of masonry, forming a ceiling or canopy.The long-drawn aisle and fretted vault. Gray.
The land belonging to a lord or nobleman, or so much land as alord or great personage kept in his own hands, for the use andsubsistence of his family.My manors, rents, revenues, l forego. Shak.
To whisper. [obs.] Shak. Holland.The Bishop of Glasgow rounding in his ear, "Ye are not a wise man," .. . he rounded likewise to the bishop, and said, "Wherefore broughtye me here" Calderwood.
Tape or braid; an ornament. Halliwell. Leere side, the leftside, as that on which a leere or ornament was worn. B. Jonson.
See Zenick.
To stir. [Obs.]He could not move nor quich at all. Spenser.
A privy. Shak.
To acquire desert; to gain value; to receive benefit; toprofit. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
To shoot out, or emit, as a dazzling light.Every eye Glared lightning, and shot forth pernicious fire. Milton.
See Pisé.
Skin of bacon. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
To praise; to worship. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Debeige.
The morning; specifically (R. C. Ch.), the first canonicalhour, succeeding to lauds.Early and late it rung, at evening and at prime. Spenser.
Realm. [Obs.] Piers Plowman.
Resembling crape.
A band in the same position as the bend sinister, but only halfas broad as the latter.
A South American butterfly (Ithonia phono) having nearlytransparent wings.
A sharp instrument used for opening veins, lancing gums, etc.;a kind of lancet. Fleam tooth, a tooth of a saw shaped like anisosceles triangle; a peg tooth. Knight.
Jelly. [Obs.] Spenser.
The East Indian leguminous tree Butea frondosa. See Gum Butea,under Gum. [Written also pales and palasa.]
A genus of grasses including the rice plant; rice.

Less; requiring to be subtracted; negative; as, a minusquantity. Minus sign (Math.), the sign [-] denoting minus, or less,prefixed to negative quantities, or quantities to be subtracted. SeeNegative sign, under Negative.
One who rows with an oar.
A glimpse, glance, or gleam. [Scot.] "He saw a glint of light."Ramsay.
To prop; to scotch. [Prov. Eng.]
Poke (Phytolacca decandra).
At work; in action. "Set awork." Shak.
A lieutenant or first officer, who is the real commander whenthe captain is unfit for his place.
To strike violently and at random, esp. with an edgedinstrument; to lay about one indiscriminately with blows; to cuthastily and carelessly.Hewing and slashing at their idle shades. Spenser.
See 1st Jeer (b).
See Arrish.
To sound. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A cactaceous plant (Nopalea cochinellifera), originallyMexican, on which the cochineal insect feeds, and from which it iscollected. The name is sometimes given to other species of Cactaceæ.
A violent assault on a fortified place; a furious attempt oftroops to enter and take a fortified place by scaling the walls,forcing the gates, or the like.
The expressed juice of apples. It is used as a beverage, formaking vinegar, and for other purposes.
See Gulf.
Ten millions; as, a crore of rupees (which is nearly$5,000,000). [East Indies] Malcolm.
To form raised work upon the outer surface of (thin metal ware)by the repercussion of a snarling iron upon the inner surface.
To hoot. [Obs.]
imp. & p. p. of Find.
An exception; a reservation; an excuse.They admit many salvos, cautions, and reservations. Eilon Basilike.
A sluice or lock, as in a river, to make it more navigable.[Obs.] Pepys.
Same as Eagre.
Raining in very small drops.
Same as Lief.
A variety of cabbage (Brassica oleracea), cultivated for itsseeds, which yield an oil valued for illuminating and lubricatingpurposes; summer rape.

To show insolent ridicule or mockery; to manifest contempt byderisive acts or language; -- often with at.Thuth from his lips prevailed with double sway, And fools who came toscoff, remained to pray. Goldsmith.
Having a site; situated. [Obs.][The garden] sited was in fruitful soil. Chaucer.
An ornament in the Corinthian capital resembling the stalk of aplant, from which the volutes and helices spring.
To breathe. [Obs.] Shenstone.
A genus of marine gastropods, having rough, and frequentlyspinose, shells, which are often highly colored inside; the rockshells. They abound in tropical seas.

In Mexico and the southwestern United States, a kind ofplastered house or hut, usually made by planting poles or timber inthe ground, filling in between them with screen work or wickerwork,and daubing one or both sides with mud or adobe mortar; also, thismethod of construction.
A soft, earthy substance, of a white, grayish, or yellowishwhite color, consisting of calcium carbonate, and having the samecomposition as common limestone.
A husband's brother; -- used in reference to leviratemarriages.
A neglected and untrained city boy; a young street Arab.In Japan, the gamins run after you, and say, 'Look at the Chinaman.'L. Oliphant.
A sapling left standing in a fallen wood. [Prov. Eng.]Halliwell.
A colloquial or humorous name for any science or branch ofknowledge.He had a smattering of mechanics, of physiology, geology, mineralogy,and all other ologies whatsoever. De Quincey.
A thick plank on the inner part of a ship's side, used tosustuan the ends of beams.
See Soncy. [Scot.] Burns.
Blessed. "This patriarch blest." Milton.White these blest sounds my ravished ear assail. Trumbull.
In fact; by the act or fact. De facto. (Law) See De facto.
A small iron rod which suspends the core of the mold in castinga shell.
A money of account in Persia, whose value varies greatly atdifferent times and places. Its average value may be reckoned atabout two and a half dollars.
A confused heap; a throng, as of persons; a jumble, as ofsounds. [Obs.]To turn prayer into a kind of lurry. Milton.
To cheat. [Colloq.] L'Estrange.
To frequent the company of wenches, or women of ill fame.
Half-roasted ore.
One who, or that which, puzzles; a difficult or inexplicablequestion or fact. Bacon.
To pack in a crate or case for transportation; as, to crate asewing machine; to crate peaches.
An instrument which consists of links and is used in measuringland.
The whortleberry, or bilberry. See Whortleberry (a).
A jest. [Obs.] Chaucer.
See Souse. [Obs.]

A white, crystalline substance, C8H7N, obtained from blueindigo, and almost all indigo derivatives, by a process of reduction.It is also formed from albuminous matter, together with skatol, byputrefaction, and by fusion with caustic potash, and is present inhuman excrement, as well as in the intestinal canal of someherbivora.
To stun or stupefy with noise; to deafen. [Scot.]
A woman's name; also, a popular name for a parrot.

Small; little; insignificant; mean; -- Same as Petty. [Obs.,except in legal language.]By what small, petit hints does the mind catch hold of and recover avanishing notion. South.Petit constable, an inferior civil officer, subordinate to the highconstable.-- Petit jury, a jury of twelve men, impaneled to try causes at thebar of a court; -- so called in distinction from the grand jury.-- Petit larceny, the stealing of goods of, or under, a certainspecified small value; -- opposed to grand larceny. The distinctionis abolished in England.-- Petit maître (. Etym: [F., lit., little master.] A fop; acoxcomb; a ladies' man. Goldsmith.-- Petit serjeanty (Eng. Law), the tenure of lands of the crown, bythe service of rendering annually some implement of war, as a bow, anarrow, a sword, a flag, etc.-- Petit treason, formerly, in England, the crime of killing aperson to whom the offender owed duty or subjection, as one'shusband, master, mistress, etc. The crime is now not distinguishedfrom murder.
See Ladykin.
Of a dazzling luster; glaring; bright; shining; smooth.Bright, crystal glass is glary. Boyle.
A strong drink; cider. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A slattern; a mawk. [Prov. Eng.]
Imposing a pecuniary penalty; consisting of, or paid as, afine.Fines, or some known mulctuary punishments. Sir W. Temple.
The part of a plow which projects downward beneath the beam,for holding the share and other working parts; -- also calledstandard, or post.
A brick or tile. Knight.
Eldest; firstborn. Blackstone.
Of or pertaining to a whale.
A Turkish open summer house or pavilion, supported by pillars.
Sour. [Obs.] Shak.
A species of shrike.
An argillaceous rock which readily splits into thin plates;argillite; argillaceous schist.
Bending down; sloping. [Obs.]
Noble. [Obs.]
Goddess of the seasons, or of the hours of the day.Lo! where the rosy-blosomed Hours, Fair Venus' train, appear. Gray.
Very small; tiny. [Colloq.]
See Gloze. Chaucer.
On fire.
To arrange in a clump or clumps; to cluster; to group.Blackmore.
See Comb.

A tree of the genus Acer, including about fifty species. A.saccharinum is the rock maple, or sugar maple, from the sap of whichsugar is made, in the United States, in great quantities, byevaporation; the red or swamp maple is A. rubrum; the silver maple,A. dasycarpum, having fruit wooly when young; the striped maple, A.Pennsylvanium, called also moosewood. The common maple of Europe isA. campestre, the sycamore maple is A. Pseudo-platanus, and theNorway maple is A. platanoides.
See Lodge, n. Raymond.
To break into crumbs or small pieces with the fingers; as, tocrumb bread. [Written also crum.]
Broken, as an ordinary; cut off, or broken at the top, as achevron, a bend, or the like.
Stock; race; family. [Obs.] Bacon.
To call into court to warrant and defend, or to make good awarranty of title.He vouches the tenant in tail, who vouches over the common vouchee.Blackstone.
A bend in a coast forming an open bay; as, the Bight of Benin.
To take aim by a sight.
pl. of Medium.

An abridgment or concise statement of a client's case, made outfor the instruction of counsel in a trial at law. This word isapplied also to a statement of the heads or points of a law argument.It was not without some reference to it that I perused many a brief.Sir J. Stephen.
To drool. [Obs.]
Any substance supposed to be capable of absorbing, retaining,and transporting contagious or infectious germs; as, woolen clothesare said to be active fomites.
To assent; to consent. [Obs.] Chaucer.
A sudden or irregular incursion in border warfare; hence, anyirregular incursion for war or spoils; a raid. Spenser.The huge Earl Doorm, . . . Bound on a foray, rolling eyes of prey.Tennyson.
p. p. & a. from Give, v.
The final adult, and usually winged, state of an insect. SeeIllust. of Ant-lion, and Army worm.
An alloy of lead and tin, of which the Chinese make teacanisters.
A bleb; a vesicle, or an elevation of the cuticle, containing atransparent watery fluid.
imp. & p. p. of Cry.
Bent without angles; crooked; curved; as, a curve line; a curvesurface.
In a manner measured by an odd number.
The erd shrew. [Scot.]

A scaup duck. See below. Scaup duck (Zoöl.), any one of severalspecies of northern ducks of the genus Aythya, or Fuligula. The adultmales are, in large part, black. The three North American speciesare: the greater scaup duck (Aythya marila, var. nearctica), calledalso broadbill, bluebill, blackhead, flock duck, flocking fowl, andraft duck; the lesser scaup duck (A. affinis), called also littlebluebill, river broadbill, and shuffler; the tufted, or ring-necked,scaup duck (A. collaris), called also black jack, ringneck, ringbill,ringbill shuffler, etc. See Illust. of Ring-necked, under Ring-necked. The common European scaup, or mussel, duck (A.marila),closely resembles the American variety.
The snout of a swine. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Full of veins; veinous; veined; as, veiny marble.
A South American carnivore (Galera barbara) allied to thegrison. The tail is long and thick. The length, including the tail,is about three feet. [Written also taira.]

A heavy locomotive for freight traffic, having three pairs ofconnected driving wheels and a two-wheeled truck. Great, or Grand,Mogul, the sovereign of the empire founded in Hindostan by theMongols under Baber in the sixteenth century. Hence, a very importantpersonage; a lord; -- sometimes only mogul. Dryden.
In making maple sugar, to complete the process of boiling downthe sirup till it is thick enough to crystallize; to approach orreach the state of granulation; -- with the preposition off. [Local,U.S.]
A line above or below a hanging net, to which the net isattached in order to strengthen it.
To spread. [Obs.] Ray.

Pertaining to, or suitable for, gypsies. Gypsy hat, a woman'sor child's broad-brimmed hat, usually of straw or felt.-- Gypsy winch, a small winch, which may be operated by a crank, orby a ratchet and pawl through a lever working up and down.
A gown or case of skin, or one trimmed or lined with fur.[Obs.]
A small Scotch coin worth about one sixth of an English penny.Sir W. Scott.
See Clake.
To cast prematurely; -- said of female beasts; as, a cow thatslinks her calf.
To strike aghast; to affright. [Obs.]Ghasted by the noise I made. Full suddenly he fled. Shak.
The Patriarch, or head of the Abyssinian Church.
To put a stop to; to bring to an end.But he, her fears to cease Sent down the meek-eyed peace. Milton.Cease, then, this impious rage. Milton
The coarse part of flax or hemp; hards.
A small, oval, transparent jellyfish, belonging to theCtenophora.
To make green.Great spring before Greened all the year. Thomson.
To inhabit. [R.] Milton.
Having jags; set with teeth; notched; uneven; as, jaggy teeth.Addison.

The fluid which is excreted from the skin of an animal; thefluid secreted by the sudoriferous glands; a transparent, colorless,acid liquid with a peculiar odor, containing some fatty acids andmineral matter; perspiration. See Perspiration.In the sweat of thy face shalt thou eat bread. Gen. iii. 19.
To foretell the fate of; to predict; to destine to. [Scot.]Jamieson.
Having strong or large thews or muscles; muscular; sinewy;strong.
A quaternary deposit, usually consisting of a fine yellowishearth, on the banks of the Rhine and other large rivers.
See Mewl, and Miaul.
A small drum used as an accompaniment to a pipe or fife, bothbeing played by the same person. [Written also tabour, and taber.]
One who tames or subdues.
A European finch (Serinus hortulanus) closely related to thecanary.
A light repast between meals; a lunch. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
A noun suffix signifying action, state, or quality; also, thatwhich relates to the action or state; as in emergence, diffidence,diligence, influence, difference, excellence. See -ance.
To tell stories or gests. [Obs.]
In a heap; huddled together. Hood.
A leper. [Obs.]
See Shawm. [Obs.] Knolles.

Any lizard of the family Geckonidæ. The geckoes are small,carnivorous, mostly nocturnal animals with large eyes and vertical,elliptical pupils. Their toes are generally expanded, and furnishedwith adhesive disks, by which they can run over walls and ceilings.They are numerous in warm countries, and a few species are found inEurope and the United States. See Wall gecko, Fanfoot.
Same as Donat. Piers Plowman.
To steal purses; to rob. [Obs. & R.]I'll purse: . . . I'll bet at bowling alleys. Beau. & Fl.
A kind of portable camera.
Winter. Shak.
A wave, or two or three successive waves, of great height andviolence, at flood tide moving up an estuary or river; -- commonlycalled the bore. See Bore.
An usher to a riding master.

Containing, or derived from, amidogen. Amido acid, an acid inwhich a portion of the nonacid hydrogen has been replaced by theamido group. The amido acids are both basic and acid.-- Amido group, amidogen, NH2.
A variety of the common cabbage (Brassica oleracea major),having curled leaves, -- much cultivated for winter use.
A scoop with a long handle, used to wash the sides of a vessel,and formerly to wet the sails or deck.
Half-rotten straw, or any like substance strewn on the ground,as over the roots of plants, to protect from heat, drought, etc., andto preserve moisture.
In a mad manner; without reason or understanding; wildly.
One who pores.
A dear; a darling. [Familiar]
Wet; moist; as, a madid eye. [R.] Beaconsfield.
Same as Doorga.
See Erst. [Obs.] Spenser.
Second best wool from Merino sheep. Gardner.
A person infected with a filthy or pestilential disease; aleper. Chaucer.Like loathsome lazars, by the hedges lay. Spenser.Lazar house a lazaretto; also, a hospital for quarantine.
A genus of chilognathous myriapods. The body is long and round,consisting of numerous smooth, equal segments, each of which bearstwo pairs of short legs. It includes the galleyworms. SeeChilognatha.
imp. of Shape. Shaped. Chaucer.
Weighed; determined; reduced to equal or standard weight; as,tared filter papers, used in weighing precipitates.
To be suitable to; to suit; to become.That name best befits thee. Milton.
Turbid; muddy; filthy. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Of or pertaining to the pubes; in the region of the pubes; as,the pubic bone; the pubic region, or the lower part of thehypogastric region. See Pubes.(b) Of or pertaining to the pubis.
A Linnæan genus of Quadrumana which included the types ofnumerous modern genera. By modern writers it is usually restricted tothe genus which includes the orang-outang.
See Waive. [Obs.] Gower.

Specifically, a small body of cavalry, light horse, ordragoons, consisting usually of about sixty men, commanded by acaptain; the unit of formation of cavalry, corresponding to thecompany in infantry. Formerly, also, a company of horse artillery; abattery.
A genus of coniferous trees, having deciduous leaves, infascicles (see Illust. of Fascicle).
See Divot.
To report by rumor; to tell.'T was rumored My father 'scaped from out the citadel. Dryden.

An instrument, consisting usually of a wireloop or noose, forremoving tumors, etc., by avulsion. Snare drum, the smaller commonmilitary drum, as distinguished from the bass drum; -- so calledbecause (in order to render it more resonant) it has stretched acrossits lower head a catgut string or strings.

A tumult; a noisy quarrel; a disturbance; a brawl; contention;discord, either between individuals or in the state.I will own that there is a haughtiness and fierceness in human naturewhich will which will cause innumerable broils, place men in whatsituation you please. Burke.
See Stirk. [Prov. Eng. & Scot.]
Of or pertaining to the calf of the leg; as, the suralarteries.
To impair or become impaired; to injure. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Infected with the mange; scabby.
Of hail. "Haily showers." Pope.
Like paste, as in color, softness, stickness. "A pastycomplexion." G. Eliot.
obs. imp. pl. of Sit. Sat. Chaucer.
To insult; to flout; to mock; to snub. [Obs.] Beau. & Fl.
Customs; habits; esp., customs conformity to which is more orless obligatory; customary law.
Moodly silent; sullen; sour; obstinate; morose; splenetic.
To cover with, or as with, a glove.
Money or other valuable thing given to evidence a contract; apledge or earnest.

To resolve into its elements, as a sentence, pointing out theseveral parts of speech, and their relation to each other bygovernment or agreement; to analyze and describe grammatically.Let him construe the letter into English, and parse it overperfectly. Ascham.
Any bird of the genus Junco, which includes several species ofNorth American finches; -- called also snowbird, or blue snowbird.

Resembling slate; having the nature, appearance, or properties,of slate; composed of thin parallel plates, capable of beingseparated by splitting; as, a slaty color or texture. Slaty cleavage(Min.), cleavage, as of rocks, into thin leaves or plates, like thoseof slate; -- applied especially to those cases in which the planes ofcleavage are not parallel to the planes of stratification. It is nowbelieved to be caused by the compression which the strata haveundergone.-- Slaty gneiss (Min.), a variety of gneiss in which the scales ofmica or crystals of hornblende, which are usually minute, form thinlaminæ, rendering the rock easily cleavable.
To loose from pins; to remove the pins from; to unfasten; as,to unpin a frock; to unpin a frame.
An awkward, clumsy fellow; a lubber. Swift.
Belonging to, or resembling, the oldest and simplest of thethree orders of architecture used by the Greeks, but ranked as secondof the five orders adopted by the Romans. See Abacus, Capital, Order.

A particular appearance or state in a regularly recurring cycleof changes with respect to quantity of illumination or form ofenlightened disk; as, the phases of the moon or planets. See Illust.under Moon.
A wild dog found in Australia, but supposed to have introducedat a very early period. It has a wolflike face, bushy tail, and areddish brown color.
A shot in which the ball struck with the cue comes in contactwith two or more balls on the table; a hitting of two or more ballswith the player's ball. In England it is called cannon.

A putting off or deferring; procrastination; lingeringinactivity; stop; detention; hindrance.Without any delay, on the morrow I sat on the judgment seat. Actsxxv. 17.The government ought to be settled without the delay of a day.Macaulay.
A barrulet, or, rarely, a bendlet, with pendants, or points,usually three, especially used as a mark of cadency to distinguish aneldest or only son while his father is still living.
A dungfork. [Scot.] Burns.
With art or skill. [Obs.]
Having the faculty of quick motion in the limbs; apt or readyto move; nimble; active; as, an agile boy; an agile tongue.Shaking it with agile hand. Cowper.

To come to for the purpose of chastising, rewarding,comforting; to come upon with reward or retribution; to appear beforeor judge; as, to visit in mercy; to visit one in wrath.[God] hath visited and redeemed his people. Like i. 68.
Nephew. [Obs.] haucer.
To strike or beat with something thick or heavy, or so as tocause a dull sound.These bastard Bretons; whom our hathers Have in their own landbeaten, bobbed, and thumped. Shak.
The time during which the sun is up, or above the horizon; thetime between sunrise and sunset.
Any leguminous plant of the genus Vicia, some species of whichare valuable for fodder. The common species is V. sativa.

Of a dark color, of various shades between black and red oryellow.Cheeks brown as the oak leaves. Longfellow.Brown Bess, the old regulation flintlock smoothbore musket, withbronzed barrel, formerly used in the British army.-- Brown bread (a) Dark colored bread; esp. a kind made of unboltedwheat flour, sometimes called in the United States Graham bread. "Hewould mouth with a beggar though she smelt brown bread and garlic."Shak. (b) Dark colored bread made of rye meal and Indian meal, or ofwheat and rye or Indian; rye and Indian bread. [U.S.] -- Brown coal,wood coal. See Lignite.-- Brown hematite or Brown iron ore (Min.), the hydrous iron oxide,limonite, which has a brown streak. See Limonite.-- Brown holland. See under Holland.-- Brown paper, dark colored paper, esp. coarse wrapping paper, madeof unbleached materials.-- Brown spar (Min.), a ferruginous variety of dolomite, in partidentical with ankerite.-- Brown stone. See Brownstone.-- Brown stout, a strong kind of proter or malt liquor.-- Brown study, a state of mental abstraction or serious reverie. W.Irving.
Pertaining to, or in the region of, the malar, or cheek bone.

A fragrant gum resin obtained chiefly tropical trees of thegenera Amyris and Canarium. A. elemifera yields Mexican elemi; C.commune, the Manila elemi. It is used in the manufacture ofvarnishes, also in ointments and plasters.
To turn round by action of wind or tide when at anchor; as, aship swings with the tide.
See Cabob, n. & v. t.
In a dull manner; stupidly; slowly; sluggishly; without life orspirit.Supinely calm and dully innocent. G. Lyttelton.
A white crystalline resinous substance extracted from gutta-percha by the action of alcohol or ether.

A morbid condition due to intestinal obstruction. It ischaracterized by complete constipation, with griping pains in theabdomen, which is greatly distended, and in the later stages byvomiting of fecal matter. Called also ileac, or iliac, passion.
To dash; to swash.
One of the upright pieces in a frame; one of the primarymembers of a frame, into which the secondary members are mortised.
A holiday. [Obs.] Bullokar.
of Day. Also adj.; as, dried apples.
See Fox, n., 7.
Consisting of, abounding in, or resembling, surf; as, a surfyshore.Scarce had they cleared the surfy waves That foam around thosefrightful caves. Moore.
Of or pertaining to the drama; appropriate to, or having thequalities of, a drama; theatrical; vivid.The emperor . . . performed his part with much dramatic effect.Motley.
for Bursteth. [Obs.]
To drink immoderately; to carouse; to booze. See Booze.
To pull or haul; as, to bowse upon a tack; to bowse away, i.e., to pull all together.
A macaw.
A short wooden club having a deeply concave face, seldom used.
A meteor or brilliant shooting star, followed by a train oflight or sparks; esp. one which explodes.
To lower, as a sail, a yard, etc.
Covered or adorned with plumes, or as with plumes; feathery."His plumy crest." Addison. "The plumy trees." J. S. Blackie.
Flame; blaze; a fire; a fireplace. [Obs. or Scot.] Burns. Inglenock, the chimney corner.-- Ingle side, Ingle cheek, the fireside.
Pertaining to, or applied to, the language of the Tuscaroras,Iroquois, Wyandots, Winnebagoes, and a part of the Sioux Indians.Schoolcraft.
A suffix used in medical terms to denote an inflammatorydisease of; as, arthritis; bronchitis, phrenitis.
A duel; also, the rules of dueling. [Obs.] Shak.
To make a loud or shrill noise. [Obs.] Golding.
Incognito. [Colloq.]Depend upon it -- he'll remain incog. Addison.
A waiting for; ambush; watch; watching; heed. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To produce young; -- said of eggs; to come forth from the egg;-- said of the young of birds, fishes, insects, etc.
To accuse of crime; to inform against. [Obs.] Foxe.
A genus of grasses, including the common oat (Avena sativa);the oat grasses.
A shereef.
A falling on and seizing, as the prey of a rapacious bird; theact of swooping.The eagle fell, . . . and carried away a whole litter of cubs at aswoop. L'Estrange.
Same as Dancetté.

Of or pertaining to Wales, or its inhabitants. Any one of numerous species of butterflies belonging to Pieris,and allied genera in which the color is usually white. See Cabbagebutterfly, under Cabbage. Black and white. See Albumen, 2.-- White of egg, the viscous pellucid fluid which surrounds the yolkin an egg, particularly in the egg of a fowl. Itlikewise contains a small amount of globulin, and traces of fats andsugar, with some inorganic matter. Heated above 60º C. it coagulatesto a solid mass, owing to the albumin which it contains. A large ruminant used in Asia and Africa for carrying burdensand for riding. The camel is remarkable for its ability to go a longtime without drinking. A beverage composed of wine or distilled liquor, water (ormilk), sugar, and the juice of lemon, with spice or mint; --specifically named from the kind of spirit used; as rum punch, claretpunch, champagne punch, etc. Milk punch, a sort of punch made withspirit, milk, sugar, spice, etc.-- Punch bowl, a large bowl in which punch is made, or from which itis served.-- Roman punch, a punch frozen and served as an ice.
Nonsecretion or defective secretion of urine; ischury.
A viola da gamba.

The small, spicy berry of a species of pepper (Piper Cubeba; inmed., Cubeba officinalis), native in Java and Borneo, but nowcultivated in various tropical countries. The dried unripe fruit ismuch used in medicine as a stimulant and purgative.
A narrow arm of the sea; an estuary; the opening of a riverinto the sea; as, the Frith of Forth.

As far as; to the place or degree that; especially, up to thetime that; till. See Till, conj.In open prospect nothing bounds our eye, Until the earth seems joinedunto the sky. Dryden.But the rest of the dead lives not again until the thousand yearswere finished. Rev. xx. 5.
Same as Lorry, or Lorrie.
To stand the consequences of; to answer for; to suffer for.Dearly I abide that boast so vain. Milton.
A baby; a dunce. [Prov. Eng.]

To form or become covered with cream; to become thick likecream; to assume the appearance of cream; hence, to grow stiff orformal; to mantle.There are a sort of men whose visages Do cream and mantle like astanding pool. Shak.
The comic actress in an opera.-- a.
To choose or elect in concert with another. [R.]Each of the hundred was to coöpt three others. Jowett (Thysyd. ).
The European throstle or song thrush (Turdus musicus).
The keel or lower outline of a bird's bill, so far as themandibular rami are united.
A salt of uric acid; as, sodium urate; ammonium urate.
See Leden. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To bear; to endure; to undergo. [Obs. or Scot.] Gower.So much woe as I have with you tholed. Chaucer.To thole the winter's steely dribble. Burns.
To alienate; to estrange; to transfer, as property orownership. [R.] "It the son alien lands." Sir M. Hale.The prince was totally aliened from all thoughts of . . . themarriage. Clarendon.
A deformity in which the foot is turned inward. See Talipes.
To rend apart. [Obs.] Sir T. Browne.
Full; complete; plenary. [Obs.]
Perhaps; possibly; peradventure.Maybe the amorous count solicits her. Shak.In a liberal and, maybe, somewhat reckless way. Tylor.
To burst. [Obs.]And both his yën braste out of his face. Chaucer.Dreadfull furies which their chains have brast. Spenser.
To stuff; to lard; to farce. [R.]Wit larded with malice, and malice forced with wit. Shak.
See Panim. [Obs.]
A place of shelter; protection; refuge. [Scot. & Prov. Eng.][Also written bield and beeld.]The random beild o' clod or stane. Burns.
Species; kind. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To burn up. [Obs.] Bacon.
Secret; secretive; faithful to a secret. [Obs.]To be holden stable and secre. Chaucer.

To explain; to resolve; to unfold; to clear up out to a resultor conclusion; as, to solve a doubt; to solve difficulties; to solvea problem.True piety would effectually solve such scruples. South.God shall solve the dark decrees of fate. Tickell.
To cover.-- n.

A dignitary under the Anglo-Saxons and Danes in England. Ofthese there were two orders, the king's thanes, who attended thekings in their courts and held lands immediately of them, and theordinary thanes, who were lords of manors and who had particularjurisdiction within their limits. After the Conquest, this title wasdisused, and baron took its place.
A piece of money, usually silver money. [Obs.] "Realms andislands were as plates dropp'd from his pocket." Shak.
A small, flat, sweetened cake of various kinds.
To glisten; to gleam. [Obs.] Prior.

To become, in some respects, different; to vary; to change; as,the weather alters almost daily; rocks or minerals alter by exposure."The law of the Medes and Persians, which altereth not." Dan. vi. 8.
An oblong rectangular piece of cloth, worn by Roman ladies, andfastened with brooches.
A narrow piece of timber which holds together large pieces; aslat; as, the sloats of a cart.

A total prohibition of intercourse with, use of, or approachto, a given person or thing under pain of death, -- an interdict ofreligious origin and authority, formerly common in the islands ofPolynesia; interdiction. [Written also tabu.]
A strengthening cross timber.
A goblin; a specter; a frightful phantom; a bogy; a bugbear.[Written also boggle.]
See Reign. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Having the heaves.
An ornament much used in Egyptian architecture, generallyasserted to have been suggested by the Egyptian water lily.
To come into view; to appear. [Scot.]It kythes bright . . . because all is dark around it. Sir W. Scott.
imp. & p. p. of Press.
See Almonry. [Obs.]
To sing; esp. to sing joyfully; to warble.And carol of love's high praise. Spenser.The gray linnets carol from the hill. Beattie.

Bad, ill, evil, or corrupt, in a greater degree; more bad orevil; less good; specifically, in poorer health; more sick; -- usedboth in a physical and moral sense.Or worse, if men worse can devise. Chaucer.[She] was nothing bettered, but rather grew worse. Mark v. 26.Evil men and seducers shall wax worse and worse. 2 Tim. iii. 13.There are men who seem to believe they are not bad while another canbe found worse. Rambler."But I love him." "Love him Worse and worse." Gay.
To face, as an embankment, with masonry, wood, or othermaterial.
Vinnewed. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.]
A contrivance, turning on a vertical axis by a handle or winch,and giving a circular motion to the ore to be washed; a stirrer.
A carved ornament on the stern of a vessel, containing a windowor the representation of one.
That which goes out, or is paid out; outlay; expenditure; --the opposite of Ant: income. Lowell.
Gray. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Shining; sheen. [Obs.] Spenser.
A small box, can, or chest to keep tea in.

A country in Southern Asia; the two peninsulas of Hither andFarther India; in a restricted sense, Hither India, or Hindostan.India ink, a nearly black pigment brought chiefly from China, usedfor water colors. It is in rolls, or in square, and consists oflampblack or ivory black and animal glue. Called also China ink. Thetrue India ink is sepia. See Sepia.-- India matting, floor matting made in China, India, etc., fromgrass and reeds; -- also called Canton, or China, matting.-- India paper, a variety of Chinese paper, of smooth but not glossysurface, used for printing from engravings, woodcuts, etc.-- India proof (Engraving), a proof impression from an engravedplate, taken on India paper.-- India rubber. See Caoutchouc.-- India-rubber tree (Bot.), any tree yielding caoutchouc, butespecially the East Indian Ficus elastica, often cultivated for itslarge, shining, elliptical leaves.
A cover; a shelter; a protection. [Archaic] Carew. C. Kingsley.

Any one of numerous species of Old World venomous makesbelonging to Vipera, Clotho, Daboia, and other genera of the familyViperidæ.There came a viper out of the heat, and fastened on his hand. Actsxxviii. 3.

One of the stages in the life history of certain rusts(Uredinales), regarded at one time as a distinct genus. It is asummer stage preceding the teleutospore, or winter stage. SeeUredinales, in the Supplement.

Any one of a class of yellowish brown solid inflammablesubstances, of vegetable origin, which are nonconductors ofelectricity, have a vitreous fracture, and are soluble in ether,alcohol, and essential oils, but not in water; specif., pine resin(see Rosin).
A spirit, or immaterial being, holding a middle place betweenmen and deities in pagan mythology.The demon kind is of an inSydenham.
A slight gleam or glimmer; a glimpse. [Prov. Eng.] Halliwell.
Murder. [Obs.] Shak.
Rock. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Same as Izedi. Taylor.
The daughter of Tantalus, and wife of Amphion, king of Thebes.Her pride in her children provoked Apollo and Diana, who slew themall. Niobe herself was changed by the gods into stone.
A plant from which layers are propagated by bending itsbranches into the soil. P. Henderson.

A prefix denoting: (a) Likeness, similarity, or connection, orthat the substance resembles, but is distinct from, that to the nameof which it is prefixed; as paraldehyde, paraconine, etc.; also, anisomeric modification. (b) Specifically: (Organ. Chem.) That twogroups or radicals substituted in the benzene nucleus are opposite,or in the respective positions 1 and 4; 2 and 5; or 3 and 6, asparaxylene; paroxybenzoic acid. Cf. Ortho-, and Meta-. Also usedadjectively.
A Russian drink distilled from rye.
A farrow. [Obs.] Perry.
A textile fabric with a nap or shag on one side, longer andsofter than the nap of velvet. Cowper.
A popular term for a bright-hued variety of some minerals; as,the rose-red cobalt bloom.
Full of humps or bunches; covered with protuberances; humped.
Timid; fearful. [R.] Thackeray.
See Silly. [Obs.] Spenser.
Like a snipe.
A variant of -hood.
A jet of steam issuing from a fissure in the earth.
See Bowl, a ball, a game.

A large genus of evergreen coniferous trees, mostly found inthe northern hemisphere. The genus formerly included the firs,spruces, larches, and hemlocks, but is now limited to those treeswhich have the primary leaves of the branchlets reduced to merescales, and the secondary ones (pine needles) acicular, and usuallyin fascicles of two to seven. See Pine.

A form of fungus which grows as indvidual rounded cells, ratherthan in a mycelium, and reproduces by budding; esp. members of theorders Endomycetales and Moniliales. Some fungi may grow both as ayeast or as a mycelium, depending on the conditions of growth. Yeastcake, a mealy cake impregnated with the live germs of the yeastplant, and used as a conveniently transportable substitute for yeast.-- Yeast plant (Bot.), the vegetable organism, or fungus, of whichbeer yeast consists. The yeast plant is composed of simple cells, orgranules, about one three-thousandth of an inch in diameter, oftenunited into filaments which reproduce by budding, and under certaincircumstances by the formation of spores. The name is extended toother ferments of the same genus. See Saccharomyces.-- Yeast powder, a baling powder, -- used instead of yeast inleavening bread.
To prey; to plunder. [Obs.] Holinshed.
of Begin.
A swift sailing boat. [Obs.]So we took a scout, very much pleased with the manner andconversation of the passengers. Pepys.
imp. of Quake. [Obs.] Spenser.
See Cozy. Dickens.
A small tube, usually curved, applied to a trumpet, horn, etc.,to change its pitch or key.
An ouch; a jewel. [Obs.] Chaucer.
One who, or that which, eats.
A prefix. See Pre-.
p. p. of Weave. Woven paper, or Wove paper, writing paperhaving an even, uniform surface, without watermarks.
Exodus; withdrawal. [Obs.]The time of the Jewish exody. Sir M. Hale.
The bulau.

Any species of sea duck of the genus Somateria, esp. Somateriamollissima, which breeds in the northern parts of Europe and America,and lines its nest with fine down (taken from its own body) which isan article of commerce; -- called also eider duck. The American eider(S. Dresseri), the king eider (S. spectabilis), and the spectacledeider (Arctonetta Fischeri) are related species. Eider down. Etym:[Cf. Icel. æ\'ebardun, Sw. eiderdun, Dan. ederduun.] Down of theeider duck, much sought after as an article of luxury.
A small haven. See Hithe. [Obs.]
pl. of Tree. " The shady treen." Fairfax.
Master; lord; teacher; -- a Jewish title of respect or honorfor a teacher or doctor of the law. "The gravest rabbies."  Milton.
A woman. See Feme, n. Femme de chambre. Etym: [F.] A lady'smaid; a chambermaid.
The substance which, added to the material of a cell wall,makes it waterproof, as in cork.
The malicious burning of a dwelling house or outhouse ofanother man, which by the common law is felony; the malicious andvoluntary firing of a building or ship. Wharton.

A straight line in space with which a definite linear magnitudetermed the pitch is associated (cf. 5th Pitch, 10 (b)). It is used toexpress the displacement of a rigid body, which may always be made toconsist of a rotation about an axis combined with a translationparallel to that axis.
A rope or halter made of flexible twigs, or withes, as ofbirch. [Scot.]
One who fits shoes to the feet; one who furnishes or puts onshoes; as, a shoer of horses.
Bookish.

A seaweed of a reddish brown color, which is sometimes eaten,as in Scotland. The true dulse is Sarcophyllis edulis; the common isRhodymenia. [Written also dillisk.]The crimson leaf of the dulse is seen To blush like a banner bathedin slaughter. Percival.
To remove a cap or cover from.
A genus of venomous ticks which attack men and animals. Thefamous Persian Argas, also called Miana bug, is A. Persicus; that ofCentral America, called talaje by the natives, is A. Talaje.
A tendon or tendonous tissue. See Tendon.
Characterized by breadth. See Breadth.
Any species of limicoline birds belonging to Himantopus andallied genera, in which the legs are remarkably long and slender.Called also longshanks, stiltbird, stilt plover, and lawyer.

To avoid slyly, by artifice, stratagem, or dexterity; to escapefrom in a covert manner; to mock by an unexpected escape; to baffle;as, to elude an officer; to elude detection, inquiry, search,comprehension; to elude the force of an argument or a blow.Me gentle Delia beckons from the plain, Then, hid in shades, eludeshe eager swain. Pope.The transition from fetichism to polytheism seems a gradual processof which the stages elude close definition. Tylor.

Pertaining to Holland, or to its inhabitants. Dutch auction.See under Auction.-- Dutch cheese, a small, pound, hard cheese, made from skim milk.-- Dutch clinker, a kind of brick made in Holland. It is yellowish,very hard, and long and narrow in shape.-- Dutch clover (Bot.), common white clover (Trifolium repens), theseed of which was largely imported into England from Holland.-- Dutch concert, a so-called concert in which all the singers singat the same time different songs. [Slang] -- Dutch courage, thecourage of partial intoxication. [Slang] Marryat.-- Dutch door, a door divided into two parts, horizontally, soarranged that the lower part can be shut and fastened, while theupper part remains open.-- Dutch foil, Dutch leaf, or Dutch gold, a kind of brass rich incopper, rolled or beaten into thin sheets, used in Holland toornament toys and paper; -- called also Dutch mineral, Dutch metal,brass foil, and bronze leaf.-- Dutch liquid (Chem.), a thin, colorless, volatile liquid,C2H4Cl2, of a sweetish taste and a pleasant ethereal odor, producedby the union of chlorine and ethylene or olefiant gas; -- called alsoDutch oil. It is so called because discovered (in 1795) by anassociation of four Hollandish chemists. See Ethylene, and Olefiant.-- Dutch oven, a tin screen for baking before an open fire orkitchen range; also, in the United States, a shallow iron kettle forbaking, with a cover to hold burning coals.-- Dutch pink, chalk, or whiting dyed yellow, and used in distemper,and for paper staining. etc. Weale.-- Dutch rush (Bot.), a species of horsetail rush or Equisetum (E.hyemale) having a rough, siliceous surface, and used for scouring andpolishing; -- called also scouring rush, and shave grass. SeeEquisetum.-- Dutch tile, a glazed and painted ornamental tile, formerly muchexported, and used in the jambs of chimneys and the like.

An Indian of a linguistic stock of tribes of the Peruvian coastwho had a developed agricultural civilization at the advent of theSpaniards, before which they had been conquered by the Incas. Theyconstructed irrigation canals which are still in use, adorned theirbuildings with bas-reliefs and frescoes, and were skilled goldsmithsand silversmiths. -- Yun"can (#), a.
To fall off from the wind; to edge away to leeward; -- saidonly of inferior craft.
To be ashamed; to feel shame. [R.]I do shame To think of what a noble strain you are. Shak.
Slippery; smooth; crafty; hypocritical. [Prov. Eng.] Slape ale,plain ale, as opposed to medicated or mixed ale. [Prov. Eng.]
To dismantle; as, to strip a ship of rigging, spars, etc.
To defeat or evade; to invalidate. Thus, in a replication, theplaintiff may deny the defendant's plea, or confess it, and avoid itby stating new matter. Blackstone.
imp. & p. p. of Hear.
A genus of dipterous insects, including the gnat and mosquito.
The service or sacrifice of the Mass.
A writ of right.
Barren land having only a thin coat of grass. [Prov. Eng.]
Noise; confusion; uproar.That, with the hurly, death itself awakes. Shak.
Surrounded by sky. [Poetic & R.] "The skyed mountain." Thomson.
Dung. [Obs. or Prov. Eng.] Ray. Scarn bee (Zoöl.), a dungbeetle.
See Æolic.
The nostrils or nasal openings, -- the anterior nares being theexternal or proper nostrils, and the posterior nares, the openings ofthe nasal cavities into the mouth or pharynx.
To collect, and reduce to order, as troops dispersed or throwninto confusion; to gather again; to reunite.
A troublesome grass, growing as a weed in grain fields; --called also chess. See Chess.
The act of snorting; the sound produced in snorting.
The snow goose. [Canadian, & Local U. S.]
An explosive consisting of ammonium nitrate, a derivative ofnitrobenzene, chlorated napthalene, and wood meal.
To dry, or make dry. Bacon.
A circle of two or more leaves, flowers, or other organs, aboutthe same part or joint of a stem.
Strong; sinewy. "His nervy knees." Keats.
See Mohr.

A member of the solar system which usually moves in anelongated orbit, approaching very near to the sun in its perihelion,and receding to a very great distance from it at its aphelion. Acomet commonly consists of three parts: the nucleus, the envelope, orcoma, and the tail; but one or more of these parts is frequentlywanting. See Illustration in Appendix.

To have a dream of; to see, or have a vision of, in sleep, orin idle fancy; -- often followed by an objective clause.Your old men shall dream dreams. Acts ii. 17.At length in sleep their bodies they compose, And dreamt the futurefight. Dryden.And still they dream that they shall still succeed. Cowper.To dream away, out, through, etc., to pass in revery or inaction; tospend in idle vagaries; as, to dream away an hour; to dream throughlife. " Why does Antony dream out his hours" Dryden.

Said of crystalline rocks which contain a relatively lowpercentage of silica, as basalt. Basic salt (Chem.), a salt formedfrom a base or hydroxide by the partial replacement of its hydrogenby a negative or acid element or radical.
A vital part; one of the vitals. [R.]
Any detergent plant, or the part of it used as a detergent, asthe roots of Agave Americana, Chlorogalum pomeridianum, etc. [Sp.Amer. & Mex.]
To cry, as a cat; to waul. [Obs.] Spenser.
To stuff; to crowd; to fill full; hence, to make hot and close;to render stifling. Sandys.His chamber was commonly stived with friends or suitors of one kindor other. Sir H. Wotton.
One who fines or purifies.
A Dravidian of a group of tribes of Orissa, India, a section ofwhom were formerly noted for their cruel human sacrifices to theearth goddess, murder of female infants, and marriage by capture.
A contraction for Violoncello.
A narrow street. [Prov. Eng.]
A kind of carp (Cyprinus gibelio); -- called also Prussiancarp.
Of or pertaining to the Tamils, or to their language. [Writtenalso Tamul.]
An old Italian silver coin, worth about ten cents.
A concave molding; a cavetto. Gwilt.
A neatling of a pigeon or other similar bird, esp. when veryfat and not fully fledged.
A young salmon two or three years old, when it has acquired itssilvery color.
See Sola.
To exalt to the dignity of a god; to deify. [Obs.] "Begoddedsaints." South.
A hand basket. [Obs.] Herrick.
An herb; a plant.
A European fish; the lyrie.
Circuit or compass.His great parts did not live within a small ambit. Milward.
A girdle. [Obs.] "Girt with a seint of silk." Chaucer.
A trumpet call for rousing soldiers; a reveille. [Obs.]Hudibras.

The nether world (according to classical mythology, the abodeof the shades, ruled over by Hades or Pluto); the invisible world;the grave.And death and Hades gave up the dead which were in them. Rev. xx. 13(Rev. Ver. ).Neither was he left in Hades, nor did his flesh see corruption. Actsii. 31 (Rev. Ver.).And in Hades he lifted up his eyes, being in torments. Luke xvi.23(Rev. Ver.).
See Phoebe.
The interval of a fifth.
To ingraft, as a tree or plant, by the insertion of a bud oreye; to inoculate.The arts of grafting and ineying. J. Philips.
A secluded, private, or obscure way; a path or road aside fromthe main one. " Take no byways." Herbert.
A kind of wig. [Obs.] Lamb.
That division of elasmobranch fishes which includes the sharks.
Indian millet and its varieties. See Sorghum.
A saddle girth made of leather, canvas, woven horsehair, orwoven grass. [Western U.S.]
A waif. [Obs.] Spenser.
See Esteem. [Obs.] Spenser.
Curtain or covering; -- applied to various membranouspartitions, especially to the soft palate. See under Palate.
Learned. [Obs.] " Lewed man or lered." Chaucer.
The whole number of cards played in one round, and consistingof as many cards as there are players.On one nice trick depends the general fate. Pope.
Be silent; be still; hush; silence.
The packet of vellum leaves in which the gold is first beateninto thin sheets.
To cut to a bevel angle; to slope the edge or surface of.
Rounded stones containing tin ore, lying at the surface of theground, and indicating a vein. Raymond.
To kindle; to inflame; to excite.And flamed with zeal of vengeance inwardly. Spenser.
The female of the ruff.
Cream; -- a term used esp. in cookery, names of liqueurs, etc.
In a coy manner; with reserve.
A small evergreen tree or shrub (Arbutus Menziesii), ofCalifornia, having a smooth bark, thick shining leaves, and ediblered berries, which are often called madroña apples. [Written alsomadroño.]

To cause to dance, or move nimbly or merrily about, or up anddown; to dandle.To dance our ringlets to the whistling wind. Shak.Thy grandsire loved thee well; Many a time he danced thee on hisknee. Shak.To dance attendance, to come and go obsequiously; to be or remain inwaiting, at the beck and call of another, with a view to please orgain favor.A man of his place, and so near our favor, To dance attendance ontheir lordships' pleasure. Shak.
A native or inhabitant of Switzerland; a Switzer; the people ofSwitzerland.
The namaycush.
The black grime or soot of coal. [Obs.] Burton.
See Saker.
Defensive armor for the thighs. [ Written also cuisse, andquish.]
Ornamented with bosses; studded.
A plank fixed beneath an object, as beneath the rudder of avessel, to protect it from injury; a plank on the ground under theend of a shore or the like.
Cleft to the middle or slightly beyond the middle; opening witha cleft; divided by a linear sinus, with straight margins.
See Pygmy. Pigmy falcon. (Zoöl.) Same as Falconet, 2 (a).
A boast. See Crack, n. [Obs.] Spenser.
One of the minute apertures between the cells in many serousmembranes.
A sort of flat custard or pie. [Obs.] Tusser.
In a dim or obscure manner; not brightly or clearly; withimperfect sight.
The gazelle.
The legs; as, to stir one's stumps. [Slang]
An honorary title given to officers of high rank in Turkey, asto governers of provinces, military commanders, etc. The earlier formwas bashaw. [Written also pacha.]
To rip; to cut open. Bacon.
